## Installation

```bash
# Clone and install in editable mode
git clone <repo-url>
cd causal-qd-illumination/implementation
pip install -e ".[dev]"

# Optional: Parquet support
pip install pyarrow
```

Requires **Python ≥ 3.10**.  Core dependencies: NumPy, SciPy, NetworkX,
scikit-learn, Numba, python-igraph, Matplotlib, Click.

Verify the installation:

```bash
$ causal-qd --version
causal-qd, version 0.1.0
```

---

## Quick Start (CLI)

### 1. Run a synthetic benchmark

The fastest way to see CausalQD in action is the built-in benchmark.  It
generates synthetic linear-Gaussian data, runs the MAP-Elites loop, and
reports structural accuracy against the known ground truth:

```bash
$ causal-qd benchmark \
    --n-nodes 5 --n-samples 500 \
    --n-generations 50 --batch-size 10 \
    --seed 42 --output benchmark_results/ --no-baselines
```

<!-- verified output -->
```
Benchmark: 5 nodes, 500 samples, seed=42
Generating synthetic data...
  True DAG has 2 edges
Running CausalQD...
=============================================
  CausalQD Experiment Summary
=============================================
  Best quality   : -32.5884
  QD-Score       : -3280.4077
  Coverage       : 0.0128
  Elites         : 32
  Evaluated      : 464
  Time (s)       : 0.0734
  SHD            : 1
  F1             : 0.5000
  Precision      : 0.5000
  Recall         : 0.5000
=============================================
```

### 2. Run on your own data

```bash
# CSV with header row (one column per variable, one row per observation)
$ causal-qd run \
    --data my_data.csv \
    --n-generations 30 --batch-size 10 \
    --seed 42 --output results/
```

Example output (on a 4-variable dataset, 300 samples):

<!-- verified output -->
```
Loading data from my_data.csv...
  Loaded 300 samples × 4 variables
Starting CausalQD (generations=30, batch=10, seed=42)...
MAP-Elites  [####################################]  100%
=============================================
  CausalQD Experiment Summary
=============================================
  Best quality   : 5.1869
  QD-Score       : -754.8908
  Coverage       : 0.0064
  Elites         : 16
  Evaluated      : 281
  Time (s)       : 25.5602
=============================================

Results saved to results/
```

### 3. Run with ground-truth evaluation

If you have a ground-truth DAG (as a CSV adjacency matrix with header), pass
it via `--ground-truth` for automatic SHD / F1 computation:

```bash
$ causal-qd run \
    --data my_data.csv \
    --n-generations 30 --batch-size 10 \
    --ground-truth true_dag.csv \
    --output results/
```

<!-- verified output -->
```
Ground-truth evaluation:
  SHD=3  F1=0.5000  Precision=0.5000  Recall=0.5000
```

### 4. Get JSON output

```bash
$ causal-qd run \
    --data my_data.csv \
    --n-generations 10 --batch-size 5 \
    --seed 42 --output results/ --output-format json
```

<!-- verified output (excerpt) -->
```json
{
  "best_quality": -2.782722770091418,
  "qd_score": -987.6417947894286,
  "coverage": 0.0044,
  "n_elites": 11,
  "n_evaluated": 45,
  "n_iterations": 10,
  "qd_score_history": [ -611.54, -654.75, ... ],
  "coverage_history": [ 0.0016, 0.002, ... ],
  "best_quality_history": [ -105.97, -80.33, ... ],
  "elapsed_seconds": 32.28
}
```

### 5. Evaluate saved results

```bash
$ causal-qd evaluate --results results/ --true-dag true_dag.csv
```

<!-- verified output -->
```
========================================
Evaluation Results
========================================
  qd_score       : -754.8908
  coverage       : 0.0064
  n_elites       : 16
  shd            : 3
  f1             : 0.5000
  precision      : 0.5000
  recall         : 0.5000
========================================
```

JSON format:

```bash
$ causal-qd evaluate --results results/ --true-dag true_dag.csv --format json
```

<!-- verified output -->
```json
{
  "qd_score": -754.8907738842302,
  "coverage": 0.0064,
  "n_elites": 16,
  "shd": 3,
  "f1": 0.5,
  "precision": 0.5,
  "recall": 0.5
}
```

### 6. Generate plots

```bash
$ causal-qd visualize --results results/ --output plots/ --format png --dpi 150
```

Generates convergence, QD-score, coverage, and summary multi-panel plots.

### 7. Compute certificates

```bash
$ causal-qd certificate \
    --results results/ --data my_data.csv \
    --n-bootstrap 100
```

### 8. Export from pandas

```bash
$ causal-qd from-pandas
```

<!-- verified output -->
```
# Export pandas DataFrame to CSV for causal-qd

import pandas as pd

df = pd.read_csv('my_data.csv')  # or build your DataFrame
# Select numeric columns and drop missing values
numeric = df.select_dtypes(include='number').dropna()
numeric.to_csv('causal_qd_input.csv', index=False)

# Then run:
#   causal-qd run --data causal_qd_input.csv --output results/
```

```bash
$ causal-qd from-pandas --format parquet
```

<!-- verified output -->
```
